-- 
Oil Options Volatility Slips Day After IEA Reveals Supply Plan

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-06-24T20:20:02Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-24/oil-options-volatility-slips-day-after-iea-reveals-supply-plan.html
Oil options volatility slipped a day
after the  International Energy Agency  said it will coordinate
the release of oil from emergency stockpiles.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
August, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a
gauge of option prices, was 31 percent as of 3 p.m. in  New York ,
down from 32.4 percent yesterday. The underlying futures rose
0.2 percent after tumbling 4.6 percent yesterday.  Crude for August delivery gained 14 cents to settle at
$91.16 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange . Prices fell
2 percent this week, the fourth straight weekly decline.  The most active contracts in electronic trading today were
August $85 puts, with 2,568 lots changing hands. They slipped 18
cents to 87 cents a barrel. September $80 puts, the next-most
active option, declined 14 cents to $1.09 a barrel with 1,732
lots trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of crude.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information on floor trading, where the
bulk of options trading occurs, the next business day.  December 2012 $80 puts were the most active options traded
in the previous session, with 10,967 lots changing hands. They
gained 58 cents to $6.64 a barrel. The next-most active options,
August $90 puts, increased $1.36 to $2.48 a barrel on volume of
9,819 lots.  Open interest was highest for December $120 calls with
41,919 contracts. Next were December $80 puts with 39,048 and
December $150 calls with 37,959.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Dan Stets at   dstets@bloomberg.net . 